MissionCommands.Message: Welcome to the Apollo 13 campaign, a collection of scenarios that will let you experience parts of the Apollo 13 mission and its maneuvers. Some of the missions will start with a PAO message like you currently hear. Wait for it to complete.

After the ascent and during the next missions, I recommend you to use the Mission Objectives UI to see when the next radio communication is scheduled to happen. This will let you know when, and how far, to time scale.
This is the first iteration of the Apollo 13 campaign and it will continue to evolve with updates and corrections. I hope you will enjoy this campaign, and with that, let us get started.
On the DSKY, go ahead and Key V37E N01E to initialize the platform.
Roger. Verify EMS is in standby.
Set EMS MODE to ΔV SET.
Roger, EMS MODE is set to ΔV SET.
Slew the ΔV ind to 6999.9 fps. Press ROGER when complete.
Rog, go ahead and set the EMS mode to ΔV.
Ok, T minus 20 minutes to launch. We will begin the final launch preparations at this time, start with the RCS jet configurations.
Verify all four AC rolls are off.
That's right, you don't have any windows, do you?
I got one little hole up there, and it looks good here.
Rog. I'm back to Main A.
Roll is 162, Pitch is 090, Zero on the Yaw.
Trans Controller Power is On and Up.
BMAGs; Roll, Pitch and Yaw are Rate 1.
Houston, this is CDR. I'm reading you loud and clear.
Ah, read you loud and clear, Joe.
VHF A, I'm going to T/R.
TVC Servo Power 1, AC1, Main A.
Okay. Secondary Coolant Loop Pump is Off.

[Open the Flight Documents (SHIFT+M), press the "APOLLO 13 MISSION DOCUMENTS" page and load the "Apollo 13, CSM Launch Checklist" pdf. Go to p.29 in the pdf to see the BOOST checklist. You can follow this page during ascent.]
Launch vehicle lights are on, STC.
This is 13, reading you loud and clear.
Roger, good luck with the mission today.
Thank you very much. We'll do our best.
Okay. Tape Recorder's Forward, and I got a gray flag.
Roger. Primary Glycol Coolant Valve, pull to Bypass.
GDC Align. Press and hold until FDAI2 matched FDAI1 and FDAI2 ball stops moving.
One-and-a-half g's. Okay, high Q coming up.
13, Houston. Go at 1. We show the cabin relieving.
Okay, you're right on at 01:30. 10 4 ... a little bit high ... we're a little bit high, about 0.4 of a mile.
2½ g's and we're looking good in alpha.
13, Houston. Stand by for Mode I Charlie.
And, 13, you are Go for staging.
We confirm inboard out, 13. You're looking good.
Got a little flash out the window.
13, Houston. Trajectory is good; thrust is good.
We confirm skirt SEP. Roger. Tower Jett; mode II, Jim. Looking good.
13, Houston. Guidance is good, and the CMC is Go.
Okay, we're Mode II; I'm set for staging.
Got them all Rate Command and hang on.
13, Houston. You are Go at 4 minutes. The little red lines are right on the little white lines down here.
Boy, we're right on. We're about a mile and two-tenths high, though, but we're right on Vi and right on H-dot.
I bet I never had such a view.
13, Houston. Coming up 5 minutes. You're looking perfect. Over.
13, Houston. Stand by for S-IVB to COI capability.
And, Houston, what's the story on engine 5?
Jim, Houston. We don't have a story on why the inboard out was early, but the other engines are Go and you are Go.
Okay. We're - we're a little bit low on H-dot, now, but that's to be expected.
Okay. We're Mode II, gentlemen, Mode II.
13, Houston. Still looking good. Your gimbals are good; trim is good.
We just checked the trim. It doesn't fit.
13, Houston. Level sense arm time, 8 plus 38 nominal; S-II cut-off time, 9 plus 48. Over.
Roger. Nominal on the level sense arm, 9:48 on the S-II cut-off.
That's affirmative, and stand by for S-IVB to orbit.
Okay, we're low on Vi. But it's not too bad.
We're right at 8 - H-dot is a little bit low; Vi is low, but that's understandable.
You're S-IVB to orbit capability now.
How's those systems, Fred? Are there any...
Okay, now, H-dot is low, Jim. S-IVB ought to pick you up.
Apollo 13, Houston. Mark, level sense arm.
Apollo 13, Houston. At 9 minutes, you're Go; the CMC is Go.
13, Houston. You are Go for staging.
Apollo 13, Houston. Stand by for mode IV capability.
Roger that, Jim. Thrust looks good.
13, Houston. You're looking good. Trajectory, guidance, CMC are all Go.
Right on 8; good on H-dot; 200 feet a second low on Visp.
Yes, I got that. Mode IV.
We're looking good, Jim; trajectory's looking good.
13, Houston. At 11 minutes, you're Go. Predicted cut-off on the S-IVB is 12 plus 34. Over.
Apollo 13, Houston. You're Go at 11½, and predicted cut-off time is 12 plus 34. Over.
Copy SECO, Jim. We're looking at the DSKY.
Apollo 13, Houston. You have a Go orbit all sources, and the booster is safe. Over.
Complete P11 and go to P00. Press ROGER when ready.
[Ascent complete, contine the journey in Mission 2]

Title: MISSION 1 - THE ASCENT
Description: The crew of Apollo 13 is in the process of preparing the craft for ascent.
